# Auth stub — `lib/auth.ts`

`lib/auth.ts` returns a hardcoded `admin@wdts.com` dev user. This is **intentional**
for v0.1. Do **not** replace it without coordinating the Azure AD integration
that scoping §4 (integration #1) and §8 N2 describe.

## Why it's a stub

- The dashboard is hosted on Azure (App Service / Container Apps) and uses
  Azure AD / Entra ID via NextAuth as its identity provider (scoping §6 Q2).
- That requires N2 (domain name), N1 (Azure subscription / resource group),
  and an app registration with the right redirect URIs — none of which are
  cleared yet.
- Wiring NextAuth before those are cleared bakes in the wrong tenant /
  redirect URI and forces a re-do.

## What replacing it looks like (v0.2 spec)

Replace `getCurrentUser()` with `getServerSession()` (NextAuth) backed by the
Azure AD provider. Do **all** of:

- Add `next-auth` + `@auth/azure-ad` (or the current canonical NextAuth Azure AD
  package — verify in `node_modules/next-auth/...` before installing).
- Add a route handler at `app/api/auth/[...nextauth]/route.ts`.
- Read `AZURE_AD_CLIENT_ID`, `AZURE_AD_CLIENT_SECRET`, `AZURE_AD_TENANT_ID`,
  `NEXTAUTH_SECRET`, `NEXTAUTH_URL` from the env. Production secrets live in
  Azure Key Vault — never in `.env`.
- Update `lib/auth.ts` so callers keep the same shape (`getCurrentUser()` →
  resolves the NextAuth session and returns the same `DevUser`-shaped object,
  or 401 if no session).
- Add a new rule `.cursor/rules/auth.mdc` that requires every route handler to
  call `getServerSession()` and return 401 on missing session.
- Add an integration test that asserts each route returns 401 unauthenticated.

## What you must not do

- Don't delete the stub file entirely; replace its body with the real
  resolver and keep the same exports so callers don't churn.
- Don't bypass the resolver for any route. If you find yourself wanting to,
  the answer is a feature flag for development with the real resolver — never
  a fall-through to "no auth".
- Don't store secrets in `.env`-committed values. The committed `.env` is for
  local DB credentials only.
- Don't hand-roll JWTs or session cookies; use NextAuth's defaults.

## During v0.1

While the stub is in place, every Server Component can call `getCurrentUser()`
without checking for null. Once the real resolver lands, every call site
becomes nullable and unauthenticated requests must redirect to sign-in (pages)
or return 401 (route handlers).
